			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I want to second Solkain's points.   Grouping and raiding are generally better than soloing for experience and items.  However, soloing is IMO a big part of this class, and especially so for a casual player.   In the wierd hours that I often keep, keeping a good group going is very hard.  It becomes pointless after 2am or so -- people are dropping off in the game and out of it; the group is spending more time trying to get and replace people than playing.
<br />

<br />
It's also hard to join a group or raid if you've got outside commitments that might call you off.  If you're in that position, it's much more responsible to not join a group or a raid.  Others suffer in time lost / etc. when they have to support you and then replace you.  Even more importantly, it's good to be able to leave without any remorse to address those outside needs.   We're still paying the EQ rent; SoE should be happy with us having RL places to live in as well <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Solo missions?  Cool idea.  Nothing wrong with it other than a blind "it's a multi-player game, silly" sort of argument.  Pretty hard to code I think though -- they should be doable by every class, and not so difficult that they require specialized AA's or somesuch, and yet be difficult enough to give a challenge.
<br />

<br />
I also second the notion that solo gameplay gives a lot of new challenge and flexibility and wonder to the game.  If it was discouraged to the point of non-viability for classes that were touted to have this ability and did so for a long time, then I am pretty sure that I and many casual and other players would leave.
<br />

<br />
Getting back to the original point of this thread.  I think that mages are at least two-sided, not one -- summoning, and damage.   Both are important.  If there's going to be a power and difficulty increase, then I think the power increase should be to both the areas, not just one.   Arguments such as "if you want to nuke be a wizard" are senseless unless they come accompanied by an ability to change characters classes after conception, with experience, skill and other points  (not to mention class-specific equipment).  Since that's not going to happen, it's only reasonable to expect that the class would not be shifted out of its current balance significantly.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
